[
    {
        "content": "<p>What is the idiomatic way to say that a field <code>K</code> is a prime field (i.e. isomorphic to either <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Q}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi><mi>p</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{F}_p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.975em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for some prime <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span>)?</p>",
        "id": 276734356,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648312808
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>here's a silly one: <code>(n : \\N) [field K] [is_fraction_ring (zmod n) K]</code>.</p>",
        "id": 276734770,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Rodriguez",
        "timestamp": 1648313452
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>or maybe that includes <code>F_p^n</code>s, never mind</p>",
        "id": 276734794,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Rodriguez",
        "timestamp": 1648313487
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One option could be to say that any morphism of fields <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L \\to K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> is an isomorphism (presumably where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> has the same universe level as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>)</p>",
        "id": 276734889,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648313609
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>that feels like a far more mathlibby definition, and leave the fact that they're isomorphic to F_p/Q as a theorem</p>",
        "id": 276734995,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Rodriguez",
        "timestamp": 1648313716
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Alternatively one could try to somehow say that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> is generated as a field by the image of the canonical ring hom from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 276735064,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648313780
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I don't know if we have a good way to say that.</p>",
        "id": 276735068,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648313789
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>why do we need them to be in the same universe?</p>",
        "id": 276735069,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Rodriguez",
        "timestamp": 1648313789
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If we want a characteristic predicate, we want to make sure that there aren't any additional universe parameters that are not necessary. So we could take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> to be in <code>Type 0</code> or in <code>Type u</code> where <code>K : Type u</code>.</p>",
        "id": 276735080,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648313833
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The two would be equivalent because there would be an isomorphism with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Q}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Q</span></span></span></span> or <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi><mi>p</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{F}_p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.975em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> which are in <code>Type 0</code>.</p>",
        "id": 276735101,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648313868
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But if we let <code>L : Type v</code> while <code>K : Type u</code>, then a priori there would be many predicates <code>is_prime_field K</code> which depend not only on <code>u</code> where <code>K : Type u</code>, but also on the <code>v</code>.</p>",
        "id": 276735154,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648313914
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We can use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib_docs/find/subfield.closure\">docs#subfield.closure</a> and say that the subfield generated by <code>empty</code> is <code>top</code>.</p>",
        "id": 276739032,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648319275
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or maybe just <code>bot = top</code> in <code>subfield</code></p>",
        "id": 276739106,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1648319356
    }
]